-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Guinness, Nation Media, Scangroup, Skye Bank
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 2010-10-08T15:29:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-08/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-nation-media-group-scangroup-shares-are-active.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rose for a
fifth day, adding 0.6 percent to close at 1,794.52 by 1:30 p.m.
in Port Louis, the highest since July 2, 2008.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index  retreated for a second day,
dropping 0.3 percent to 81.55 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  rose for the first
day in three, climbing 0.6 percent to close at 23,772.4 by 1
p.m. in Lagos, data from the exchange’s website show. Namibia’s
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  gained 0.3 percent to 807.48 by the 5
p.m. close in Windhoek. The Ghana Stock Exchange All Share Index
retreated 0.1 percent to 6,687.02 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra,
a second day of decreases.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Guinness Nigeria Plc  (GUINNESS NL) rose to the highest
level in more than eight years, gaining 8.67 naira, or the
maximum daily limit of 5 percent, to 182.07 naira, on bets the
country’s second-biggest brewer by market value increased market
share and volumes in the year through June, CSL Stockbrokers
Ltd. said.  “We suspect that Guinness grew its total beer volumes by
about 17 percent during its 2010 fiscal year,”  Tunde Abidoye , a
Lagos-based analyst at CSL, said in an e-mailed response to
questions.  Nation Media Group Ltd.  (NMG KN), East Africa’s biggest
media company, increased 2 shillings, or 1.2 percent, to 170
shillings, the highest since Aug. 1, 2008. The Rwandan market
regulator approved a plan for the company to trade its shares
there from Nov. 2, helping boost trading volumes on the bourse,
 Robert Mathu , the executive director of the capital market
regulator, said in an interview yesterday.  Scangroup Ltd.  (SCAN KN), East Africa’s biggest advertising
company and Kenya’s best-performing stock this year, fell from
the highest level since its shares started trading in 2006,
falling 1 shilling, or 1.3 percent, to 74.5 shillings, on
speculation gains were overdone,  Renaldo D’souza , an analyst at
Nairobi’s Genghis Capital Ltd., said in a phone interview.  Skye Bank Plc  (SKYEBANK NL), a Nigerian lender, increased
for the first time in four days, adding 20 kobo, or 2.9 percent,
to 7.04 naira after its price estimate was raised by 9.5 percent
to 11.5 naira at CSL Stockbrokers Ltd.  “We expect risk asset growth, recoveries and modest
improvements in the operating environment to drive profit-
before-tax growth of 30 percent quarter-on-quarter on average,”
Lagos-based analysts Olubunmi Asaolu and  Gbenga Sholotan  wrote
in a note to clients dated today.  To contact the reporters on this story:
